Quota Module Integration Notes
Here's a quick breakdown of how the new quota module works, how it processes statuses, and how we're using it in the pipeline.

How the module works
Instead of doing manual click-ops in the GCP console, we built tf-mod-quota-management to talk directly to the Google Cloud Quotas API. You pass it a list of quotas (with or without specific regions), and it formats them into valid API requests and shoots them off to Google.

Avoiding the "Decrease" Error
Earlier we saw an error about LIMIT_DECREASE_BELOW_USAGE. GCP throws this whenever it thinks you are trying to lower your quota below your default project limits. To get around this without adding complicated permission workarounds, we just make sure the quota values we request are always higher than the organization defaults. As long as it's an increase, the request goes through cleanly.

How we calculate the status
Quota requests aren't always instant—they happen in the background. To give our DTO a clean status to read, we added a small piece of logic to the Terraform outputs that looks at Google's response and translates it:

PROCESSING: Google's API says reconciling = true. They are still actively thinking about the request.
APPLIED: Google says reconciling is done, and the quota we actually got matches the quota we asked for. Basically, it was auto-approved.
PENDING_GCP_REVIEW: Reconciling is done, but the numbers don't match. This happens when a request is so big (like 15,000 A2 CPUs) that it gets dumped into a manual review queue at Google. In this case, we also capture the request_number so we have the actual Google support ticket ID.
The Two-Pass Pipeline Strategy
Because our infra pipeline already runs twice, we get to use that to our advantage to handle the delay:

First Pipeline Run: Terraform submits the quotas. Google says "we're working on it." Terraform outputs PROCESSING, and the DTO records that.
Second Pipeline Run: A few minutes later, the pipeline runs again. Terraform automatically checks Google for an update. By now, Google is usually done, so Terraform calculates the new status and outputs either APPLIED or PENDING_GCP_REVIEW. The DTO grabs this updated state and pushes the final result.
